            "Here's an overview of React 19 features in 2025:\n\n## React 19 Release Timeline\n\nReact 19 dropped in December 2024, and this is the third release in the last year, following React 19 in December and React 19.1 in June.(no content)The latest version is v19.2.1 (December, 2025).\n\n## Key React 19 Features\n\n### Server Components\nReact Server Components, introduced in experimental form earlier, are now fully stable in React 19. They allow you to build components that render on the server without sending unnecessary JavaScript to the client, improving performance and reducing bundle size.\n\n### React Compiler\nReact 19 introduces a built-in compiler that transforms React components into highly optimized JavaScript code. This compiler handles rendering and state updates autonomously, reducing the need for hooks like useMemo, useCallback, and memo. The result is cleaner, more efficient code and improved runtime performance.\n\n### Actions API & Server Actions\nReact 19 introduces Server Actions, designed to replace the traditional use of REST/GraphQL APIs for many use cases in apps using frameworks like Next.js and Remix. Form submissions, data mutations, and server interactions become straightforward.\n\n### New Hooks\nNew hooks introduced include useActionState, useFormStatus, and useOptimistic.\n\n### The `use` API\nIn React 19, a new API called `use` allows reading resources in render. For example, you can read a promise with use, and React will Suspend until the promise resolves.\n\n### Concurrent Rendering\nReact 19 enables Concurrent Rendering by default, allowing React to interrupt and pause rendering work. This prevents long renders from blocking the main thread and freezing the UI.\n\n### Document Metadata Support\nNo more relying on external libraries like React Helmet. React 19 lets you manage `<title>` and `<meta>` tags directly inside components.\n\n## React 19.2 New Features (October 2025)\n\nReact 19.2 includes new features like `<Activity />`, useEffectEvent, cacheSignal, Performance Tracks, and Partial Pre-rendering.(no content)The `<Activity>` component lets you break your app into \"activities\" that can be controlled and prioritized. In React 19.2, Activity supports two modes: visible and hidden.(no content)Partial Pre-rendering allows you to pre-render the static parts of your app and serve it from a CDN, and then resume rendering the shell to fill it in with dynamic content later.\n\n## Performance Improvements\nReact 19 expands automatic batching to more scenarios such as promises, setTimeout, and native event handlers, resulting in fewer renders and better performance\u2014specifically a 32% reduction in render cycles during heavy updates."
